<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910416-0026</DOCNO><DOCID>910416-0026.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Cincinnati Bell Inc.:   First-Period Profit Fell 15%   And Revenue Increased 24%</HL><DATE>04/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CSN</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>OHIO (OH)</RE><LP>   Cincinnati Bell Inc., Cincinnati, said first-quarterearnings fell 15%, reflecting increased interest expense andhigher federal income taxes.   Earnings dropped to $15.5 million, or 24 cents a share,from $18.3 million, or 29 cents a share. Revenue rose 24% to$274.7 million from $221.3 million.</LP><TEXT>   The company, which is the parent of Cincinnati BellTelephone, said that interest expense jumped 35% because of abig program to expand and update the company's network. Atthe same time, a reduction in tax benefits resulted in a 42%increase in federal income taxes.   Chairman D.H. Hibbard told shareholders at the company'sannual meeting that the year ahead will be &quot;challenging.&quot; Butbarring a big drop in the economy, &quot;we expect improvedearnings as the year progresses.&quot; Nevertheless, the companysaid the phone unit's contribution to net income is expectedto drop again in 1991, the third straight annual decline.   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,Cincinnati Bell shares closed at $24.50, down 25 cents.</TEXT></DOC>